V Need for Speed: An escape takes place in America.
Overview
What should have been a carefree walk turned into a routine morning trip to work because of a series of completely inappropriate and reckless mistakes.
The ambitions were met to a certain extent, but that was not important, since no one clearly wanted to do any extra work.
There was great hope until the release of the new version with the title "Friend" subtitle.
It was expected that it would move the previous series of the Need For Speed in a new direction; demonstration versions indicated that playing would take a decent place in the racing genre.
We were curious to see parts of the game where the main hero gets out of the car and runs.
As is often the case with NFS, it is very different from what we expected.
The game is a pretty good arcade race, but the overall impression is that there are a few unnecessary mistakes that have been in this series for several years.
So it's not really a mistake, it's an unexplained statement from the developers.
The adventure starts very well.
You're a part of a story whose main character, Jack, decides to solve some personal problems by participating in an illegal race through America.
You're sitting in a car on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your job is to get to New York first.
This idea has some interesting features.
The march consists of 10 stages divided into more than fifty races.
This means that each race takes its course, separate stages take place in a diverse and interesting environment.
So there's no feeling that the same thing happens all the time.
Although the schedule is at the same level as in previous parts of the series, it is a pleasure to see some of the routes.
Still, the game does not give rise to strong emotions.
Although driving through the desert, in the autumn suburbs or in the snowy mountains, it is pleasant.
In addition, the races are sometimes rekindled by unusual detail.
For example, in the desert you are caught in a sandstorm that greatly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, the mountains need to be careful not to fall under an avalanche.
Some races are pretty well organized.
There are only a few varieties, but that's enough.
For a while you are trying to outrun several rivals (usually a regular race); then you are trying to improve time (a standard race with a second meter); or you are competing with one opponent.
Among other things, from time to time, you encounter a police force that makes your task even more difficult.
The components outside the car are new.
It's just an interactive animation, where most of the time Jack's running away from someone and you have to help him by pressing the right buttons at the right time.
It's no big deal.
Although it is surprising that these fragments are much smaller than you could expect (just three to be accurate).
In fact, it turns out that it's good for the game because it's not boring; given all the above, it's one of the things that makes the game more fun.
The racing model follows previous models.
This means that it is no longer something special, but that is not an inadequacy.
If you're looking for real life imitation, you'll have to look elsewhere.
Still, this driving model is very suitable for dynamic racing, although there are better options in the market.
So far, so good.
However, after a while, problems begin.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model isn't that good.
You don't expect such a game to change and clash, but if you don't have any idea of a collision with an object, how your car behaves, something's wrong.
Usually, by bending or passing by cars in a dense stream, you sometimes have a slight touch on another car, but sometimes in a relatively similar situation, your car starts to derail.
Or it's broken.
It's not really important because of the remission system, but that's enough to spoil the fun.
The restarts are so arranged that if you break or leave the route far away, the game will bring you back to the point where it was interrupted.
However, only five restarts are available for each race.
If you use them all, you'll have to start the race from the beginning.
It's useful if something doesn't work, but you can't rely on it completely.
There are times when restarts are not enough, and you have to learn to know a certain section of the race.
An important lack of play is the fact that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some turns need to go in a certain way, otherwise you just won't fit in.
In other cases, you meet civilian cars in a certain location in the same configuration, regardless of whether you come first, fifth, five seconds sooner or later.
This is especially annoying in situations where you see your opponent passing easily between two cars moving in the opposite direction, while when you are in the opposite direction, the cars are already in a position that you either need to move around or drop the speed.
It doesn't matter when you're next to them; everything's so arranged that the situation always happens right in front of your nose.
The rivals have other advantages.
During the game, you find several places where, regardless of time, the same rival chases you in the same place.
It's particularly obvious at the end of the game, on a long bridge where you're going in the opposite direction.
Obviously, your opponent must stand before you in spite of anything.
