Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five public tourist agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: Čekok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
Since travel to the West was severely restricted, tourism agencies at that time mostly sold tours to the socialist bloc countries.
Czech tourists were thus on their way to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Soci, Crime on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (both countries on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and the Yugoslav regime then returned to the West, resulting in significant restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel by himself, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation from that country was needed; otherwise, individual travel was not possible.
At the time, travel agencies offered to travel west, but they had to stand in line all night with a sleeping bag or have "good friends" in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
The currency permit was necessary for travel to the West, not given to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not freely convertible; it was not possible to obtain funds (Western currency) for travel to the West without a currency permit.
Most frequent vacations were held at home, resulting in a large number of cottages and summer homes, and this habit continues today.
Since 1989, Czech tourism has thus survived the present revolution.
While prior to 1989 holidays in the GDR or Bulgaria were the culmination of our travels, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million vacations in countries around the world.
The great paradox that we no longer realize is that, until 1989, we were unable to attend Croatia ' s most popular present because it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the very beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to the neighbouring countries of Western Europe was lifted, which marked the beginning of a huge wave of short journeys mainly in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't afford to travel to the West, and everyone wanted to go there at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in tent parks because their income at the time was not enough for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism at that time was the desire to bring their own food (conservations, salami, etc.) to save money.
Another important point is the introduction of a freely convertible Czech crown, and after decades our tourists can finally freely buy the Western currency.
Our standard of living and average income grew, leading to another important circumstance around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has allowed travel agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines.
By the end of the 1990s, it was not necessary to have a visa to visit virtually all developed world countries, except the United States, which made our travels even easier.
The next major event in the history of the journeys since the revolution occurred in 2000 and the great demand led to the historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to the exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have transported Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, which will take twelve exotic routes from the Czech Republic in winter.
At present, some 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another important development of this period, which symbolizes our development since the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States lifted the need for a visa for Czech tourists, and our country has therefore joined the world's most developed countries forever.
For the first time in the history of 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%); and for the first time in history, they spent more than 15,000 crowns per person on vacation abroad, including their expenses at the destination.
