The Court will approve the digital television transition in Mexico in 2015
The replacement of analog signals for digital signals is one of the most important changes that have occurred to the world in recent years.
The Supreme Court ( Supreme Court) rejected the constitutional claims made by the Senate and the House of Representatives against the Presidential Decree, which transposed the so-called digital television switch from 2021 to 2015, as eight votes were not cast for its annulment.
A minority of four ministers, including the President of the Court, Juan Silva Mesa, felt that President Felipe Calderon had not exceeded his authority by issuing a decree detailing actions to move to digital terrestrial television.
As a result, the constitutional claims claimed by the Senate were rejected by the absence of a qualified majority of the eight votes required for the court to rule on the constitutionality or non-constitutionality of the decree and it remains in force.
The draft statement, prepared by the Minister Olgo Sanchez Cordero, proposed to declare a decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of the radio and television programme was a law established by law for the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Caffetel), in violation of the principles of hierarchical subordination and the legislative reserve.
Only Salvidar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sanchez Cordero voted in favour of the project.
On this argument both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies held two constitutional debates to refute the decree and to support complaints, Minister Sanchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions referred to therein concerning the transition to digital broadcasting.
At the ministerial meeting, it was also decided to reject the requirement of the Chamber of Deputies without entering into a discussion of the draft, also under the responsibility of Minister Sanchez Cordero.
In his speech, the Prime Minister said that he disagreed with the project's arguments in the sense that the federal executive could not determine the general rules for measures to be prepared by the Government administration.
“I also do not think that if this were to happen, it would affect the autonomy of the governing body” and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas, such as the telecommunications sector, was relevant to the federal executive, which had a constitutional mandate, the government of the State.
The replacement of analog signals for digital -- one of the most important changes that have occurred in recent years -- has resulted in better use of the radio spectrum, better quality of the signal and more channels.
Postponing the transition, he said, would mean postponing the benefits of transforming into a digital form, which includes meeting public needs, which not only has a technical dimension, “because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues”.
These issues, he said, “are requiring the work of the entire system, which is constituted in the principle of public economic governance, includes a group of authorities that are united by the Constitution in the State executive branch”.
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world had already completed the transition to digital broadcasting and had done so with the help of the executive, despite the existence of highly specialized technical institutions.
It cannot be concluded, therefore, that the Government, by adopting the decree under discussion, which in any case affects the competence of the Congress, ensures, in the administrative sphere, compliance with the laws adopted by the Legislative Assembly, he said.
In Michoakana, the possibility of calculating "voice by vote" is analysed.
According to the data submitted to the ERW, the difference between the first and second seats in the governorial elections is only 27 per cent, even without a counting of 879 votes from the total of 6.074 protocols.
The possibility of counting the “voice vote” is real with regard to the election process this year in Michoakana, where the difference between the first and second places in the Governor's elections is only 27 per cent, even without a calculation of 879 votes from the total number of 6.074 protocols.
In light of this, the President of the General Council of the Institute of Elections, Michoakana (IVM), Maria de Los Angeles Lianderal Zaragos, recalled that a few days ago, on 9 November, the electoral corps had approved a set of principles to harmonize local rules with federal electoral reform.
As should be recalled, Michoacan did not adopt the Constitution or the State Electoral Code or the Law on Electoral Law, since the State Congress approved reforms shortly before the legal date for their entry into force in the electoral process, and Governor Leonean the Year of the Engagement did not include its publication within the time limit set by the law in the State Official Gazette, stating that he had some objections.
