In an interview on the possibility of “vote vote”, Maria de los Angeles Lianderal argued that, with the adoption of appropriate principles, the General Council of IVM would be able to submit a partial or full calculation of votes to the local electoral body.
For example, partial recalculation of one or more elective urns may take place on condition that: the results of the protocols do not coincide; there is no balloting and counting of the documents in the urn; or there are obvious errors or corrections in the protocol.
In addition, the overall roll-over of votes in all elections can occur when there is a sign that there is a difference between the alleged candidate winner of the elections under consideration and those who have won second place in the vote is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that at the beginning of the session there is a request from the party representative and/or coalition that issued the second of the candidates mentioned.
A general recalculation of votes will also take place if, at the end of the normal calculation, it is established that the difference between the winner and the candidate who took the second place is less than or equal to one per cent, provided that there is a request from the political party whose candidate took the second place, in the event of the exclusion of the ballot boxes that were taken into account in partial conversion.
