His lecture The technological view of pits read in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry reported that the laboratory for which he was responsible was developing a polymer modified bitumen for producing a mixture with characteristics close to bitumen, but with better resistance at both high and low temperatures.
Errera Naher said that this type of modified bitumen could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, as in some cities in the north, to improve the quality of roads and thus to counteract the education of pits.
He explained that bitumen, the hardest part of oil is a sequence of hydrocarbons, some of them a high molecular mass called asphalt, and others a low molecular mass called maltene, which together give road coverage to its characteristic viscosity.
The insatiable behavior of bitumen is the fact that at high temperatures of about 180 degrees he behaves as liquid, at 120 degrees he is very narrow, and at 50 degrees Celsius he retains almost a firm condition, while at very low temperatures the bitumen becomes fragile, he said.
This means that the resistance to street asphalt is not permanent, but changing during the day, depending on natural conditions and temperature, said a chemical engineer.
A scholar observed that Mexico City’s streets were mostly covered with flexible cover, consisting of six layers of material, three of which included bitumen.
Among the top layers are a bitumen made of small stones that are lowered into bitumen and then suspended.
Every stone that makes up this cover said it was buried in a bitumen.
When driving vehicles and exerting efforts, it helps forces to distribute very well by road.
If it were a modified asphalt, they'd be even better distributed, said a chemical engineer.
On the asphalt coating, he added, the last layer, called the layer of wear, made of small stone, was actually sand also wrapped in asphalt.
Since it is a layer that will interact with the wheels of transport, it must have more resistance than asphalt cover and provide road workouts.
As part of the road surface, which will receive and disseminate these efforts, the layer of wear also requires adequate thickness and must be taken into account the material from which it is made.
The weather, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, were also very important factors for consideration, especially water, he said, because it had a significant impact on the asphalt condition.
When the ground is gray, the water penetrates into the surface and is difficult to get out of it, it causes all layers of surfaces to soften and therefore to educate the pits.
In the education of pits, he said that the layer of wear was first and only then affected the bitumen, but the damage did not occur immediately, the process of which should be considered with the first signs of ongoing repair programmes.
A member of the National System of Researchers also explained that transport load is another important factor in the formation of holes, and therefore the thickness of each layer of coating must always be linked to the transport load and it is necessary to ensure that this requirement is met in order to prevent the frequent occurrence of pits.
Rafael Errera said that relative bitumen still needs to be studied and done, for example, bitumen emulsions that are already on the market in other countries and even help to make pits easily and without using high temperatures.
