Austria
Introduction to the Constitution of the “Golden Rules” of the budget
The head of a large coalition of Social Democrats and Christian Democrats in Austria decided on Tuesday to write a budget “golden rule” into the constitution to reduce the budget deficit and thus avoid possible decline in Austrian public credit rating agencies (Trino A).
Social Democrat Chancellor Werner Faymann personally announced this decision at the end of the ministerial meeting, with Austrian public debt of 74.6 per cent, which is significantly higher than the 60 per cent ceiling set by the Maastricht Treaty, but below the public debt of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
If Austria's capacity to pay fell by only one point, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay interest of three thousand million euros more each year, the Vice Chancellor and Minister for Foreign Affairs of the Christian Democrats Michael Spindelegger argued.
Austria thus met the requirement of the Eurozone summit on 26 October in Brussels; Heads of State and Government demanded that budgetary deficits be reduced by the end of 2012 and that government accounts be returned to balance through a constitution or an equivalent law.
The Austrian Government's decision recalls the “German model” because Germany was the first European country to adopt the “rule”.
By 2017, the structural deficit in the State budget should be reduced by 0.75 per cent of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and the structural deficit in the federal State budget should not exceed 0.35 per cent of GDP in any year, and land, like the communes, should represent balanced budgets.
The aim is to obligate the public debt to fall below the 60 per cent mark of the Maastricht Treaty by 2020/2021.
