Energy policy:
Facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is a topic on which a decision cannot be taken after a short discussion or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly affects the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is a healthy trend that electoral meetings give rise to reflection on the proportion and place of nuclear energy.
The dispute will not bear fruit until all the economic, social and environmental implications of the proposed options have been examined.
France must build its opinion on objective facts and on rational data.
Now we are 7,000 people on the planet, demographic development will lead to a doubling of the electricity demand by 2050, unless the vast majority of the world's population is deprived of vital elements.
During the same period, it will be necessary to fill the growing resource shortfall in order to continue to produce electricity constantly, without forgetting the crucial need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate imbalance, a topic that has disappeared from environmental debates.
The Fuchsim accident doesn't change any of these factors.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to renounce nuclear energy.
This is not the case of Belgium, which makes its decision dependent on the need to find a source capable of replacing nuclear energy, or Switzerland, which intends to build only the most modern reactors.
On the other hand, the UK, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil are few of those who are continuing their projects.
The United States decided, after Fuchsima, to add one installation to its set, to resume the construction of the station, which was interrupted after the accident in Tri Mail Island.
Although the German renewable energy model is sometimes cited as an example, the reality is contrary to this argument.
Berlin ' s choice will result in an increase in the cost of electricity, an increase in energy dependence, compounded by the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, carbon dioxide emissions from the construction of gas and coal stations.
Within a few months, all these unpleasant effects will be felt.
The example of Denmark should be considered.
The European turbine champion, from which it receives 30 per cent of its electricity, is also the largest consumer of coal and gas because of the disruptive wind; hence carbon dioxide emissions and electricity prices are 65 per cent and 50 per cent higher, respectively, than on average in Europe.
On the other hand, thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbours pay 40% more for electricity than French households.
Since in a globalized economy, the price of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and the supply of industrial equipment in the national territory, French companies benefit from cheap electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in nuclear energy will lead to a significant increase in the cost of electricity, which will make illustrative beautiful declarations of our country ' s new industrialization and protection of purchasing power.
The price most French people refuse to pay, especially because they do not object to this kind of energy in principle.
It should be remembered that the country's energy policy has made it possible to create an industry of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Strongly export-oriented, it attracts a whole range of specialized small and medium-sized enterprises on international trade and creates many jobs that cannot be moved to another industry.
If France had decided to abandon nuclear energy, it would have to sacrifice a large number of these enterprises and lose 6,000 million euros a year from the export of French nuclear equipment and services.
Which electric engineer will order EPR to work for sixty years if its manufacturer is scheduled to close?
To solve the equation of energy, it must be recognized that there are no divine or devilish sources of energy.
The development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions by Areva demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear energy, maintaining the highest level of security is undoubtedly a vital issue
In France, we have a security authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing energy centres, such as Flamanville.
Our teams, whose professionalism is universally recognized, have the same obsession with security.
Over 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, Tri-Mayal Island, occurred under normal operating conditions, but without any human or environmental effects.
In Chernobyl a reactor device and an unforgivable human error led to tragedy.
In Fukusim, some people seem to forget that the accident occurred as a result of two natural disasters of an unprecedented force that resulted in the death of tens of thousands.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it has derived from the two previous ones.
The fruit of this step and the collaboration between the security authorities, operators and French and German constructors, EPR, is presented by the project to combat such phenomena.
As it is considered by all energy professionals who want to build a reactor, the suspension of its construction in Flamanville will be a great gift to Areva and EDF competitors, clearing the way for them to win leadership in the imminent development of nuclear energy.
It is necessary and legitimate to seek the best combination of energy sources for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotions, dogmas and prejudices to prevail in a dispute that is so important for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
