North Stream, new gates for the entry of Russian gas into Europe.
The North Stream pipeline, connecting Western Europe and Russia directly to the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has been launched.
It is designed to provide gas equivalent to 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian giant gas producer, wanted to celebrate this event with a pump.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of State and Government, took part in last Tuesday on the Baltic coast, between the performance of the orchestra and the snacks sought, the opening of the North Stream, a new pipeline that directly connects Russia and Germany under water.
German Chancellor Angel Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fiyon and his Dutch colleague, Mart Rutte, together turned a symbolic valve to control the flow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
A new 27,500 million additional cubic metres of gas pipeline will flow each year to Western Europe on the first 1,224 km pipeline connecting the Leningrad region to the Mecklenburg-Pomorania land.
The second pipeline should be ready by the end of 2012, providing a total of 55,000 cubic metres of gas equivalent to all French consumption.
The possibility of building a third pipeline in the same direction is already under discussion.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge project is a victory.
The project met the fierce resistance of Poland and the Baltic States.
In fact, the North Stream will allow the gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries will lose some of their power: they will find it more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to deny access to Western European markets.
At the most tense moment of the debate, Warsaw did not stop before comparing the North Stream with the new Germano-Soviet Pact, suggesting an alliance between Hitler and Stalin with a view to occupying Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically sensitive.
In supporting this Russian project, Western Europe is making its deliveries more secure.
But at the cost of depriving Europe of energy, because the project has created a gateway between Eastern and Western Europe.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to achieve its understanding of the direct union between Russia and the rich Western countries, which consume large amounts of gas and whose own stocks are already at large.
"This pipeline is part of the cooperation with Russia, a new artery that binds us organically," said François Fiona, opening up the pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are important both political and economic.
All of this explains the wide smiles on the faces of the heads of Gazprom, who were present in large quantities in Lubmin, the arrival point of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater pipeline is made of steel locked in concrete to protect it from anchor ships.
